issues.description: ExcellenceLand declares the attribute 'rides' as List<Ride> (per problem statement) but the solution's getter getRides() returns a Set<Ride>. This is a structural mismatch between the attribute type expected by the exercise and the getter's return type in the solution. Students following the instruction to add a public getter for the rides attribute would naturally implement a getter returning List<Ride>, so the solution's Set return type is inconsistent and may cause confusion or failing tests.
issues.suggested_fix: Make the getter's return type consistent with the declared attribute type. Change the solution's getRides() signature to return List<Ride> (e.g. public List<Ride> getRides()) and return a defensive copy such as new ArrayList<>(rides) or Collections.unmodifiableList(rides). Alternatively, if the intended model is to expose a Set, update the problem statement and attribute declaration to use Set<Ride> so all artifacts agree.
